==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phosgene
<hw>Phos"gene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>fw^s</grk>
light + the root of <grk>gi`gnesqai</grk> to be born: cf. F.
<ets>phosg⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld>
<def>Producing, or produced by, the action of light; -- used
specifically to designate a gas also called carbonyl chloride. See
<er>phosgene</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and <er>Carbonyl</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>phosgene</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: phosgene
<hw>phos"gene</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧s"j⟦emac⟧n <it>or</it>
f⟦ocr⟧z"j⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A reactive
chemical substance (<chform>COCl2</chform>), also called
<altname>carbonyl choride</altname>, used in synthesis of numerous
substances. In the First World War it was also used as a poisonous gas
in combat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phosgenite</ent>⟦br⟧
